segments.text: economic forces play a great role in shaping any community.
How would you say that economic influence has been an impact in planning in Austin?
Austin's been very fortunate, as I think you'll find most centers of government.
With the high percentage of government employment,
Austin's been immune from the business cycle.
Recessions don't tend to hit Austin.
Unemployment doesn't tend to hit Austin.
We've always had one of the lowest unemployment in the entire state, if not the nation.
For a city in the size category.
Well, for any city, really.
For any city.
I think it's characteristic of most centers of government.
So Austin has not been diversified.
It's been made up of three sectors, government, military, which is not a tremendous amount, but it's significant, and the city of Austin.
The city of Austin is one of the largest employers in the entire area.
Primarily because they own the utility system, there's over 8,000 employees in the city of Austin.

It's been in the past five years, or maybe since the beginning of the Austin Memorial Program in the early 70s, that the Chamber of Commerce began a very strong and well-financed operation to diversify Austin's economy.
That has resulted over the past three years with a very noticeable and predictable shift of electronics manufacturing
from Silicon Valley in California near San Francisco.
Firms are coming to Austin to establish new plants.
There's very good reasons why they're doing that.
They find that in California they're robbing from each other now for the talent pool.
And here's Austin with a huge university, a tremendously good environment, and a new opportunity.
Well IBM came, Texas Instruments came,
Now we find Data General Corporation coming.
We find three or four other computer firms moving in from Silicon Valley and other parts of the country.
And we see Austin's electronic manufacturing employment skyrocketing.
As an example, five years ago, there might have been two lines of advertising for electrical engineering people
semiconductor people.
Now there's two pages of them.
And Austin's headed down the same road as Silicon Valley.
There will be a saturation, in my view, in the next ten years of electronics firms.
As a result, Austin is liable to face the same kind of activity that Silicon Valley had.
A tremendous competition for labor, increased labor costs, and of course with that will come greater in-migration
more white collar and higher educated people and you will see Austin continue to attract the white collar, high income pool of people.
Where has that type of so-called clean industry been sown in Austin?
Anywhere they want.
Anywhere they want.
Undeveloped land usually or has land been cleared, let's say slum clearance?
No, there's been no clearance.
There has been no centralization either.
IBM is just going through a doubling in the size of its plant.
Texas Instruments, about 8, 9, 10 miles away, outside the city limits, was only annexed a few years ago.
There's two large firms in the south just coming in.
There's one in the west.
Motorola has its second plant location.
It has a large semiconductor facility on the east side.
Tracor Corporation, which is a large electronics manufacturer, is on the east side.
And so they're just ringing the city.
There has not been a dedicated interest because of the price of cheap land.
And the availability of land, there's not been any interest in coming in and going to the expense of clearing and going into an inner city.
Mobility is easy in Austin.
It doesn't take very long to get north, south, east, or west.
And so they choose the cheapest alternative that they can.
Do planners receive a great deal of problems, though,
in that type of sphere where industry is more or less encircled with city and transportation needs have to be taken care of, new residential patterns are established.
How are these planned for?
I'd say right now, from my knowledge, they're not being planned for.
They're accepted.
The city of Austin many years ago began the development of ring freeways.

and though citizens have expressed opposition to that, we find that a significant highway's been built right through the hill country, significant bridge is going to be built right over the lake that was not really beneficial.
No one wanted it to happen, but the state did it anyway.
Tremendous conflicts there.
I see Austin continuing down the road of an inner loop, and then an outer loop,
virtually the same shape that American cities have taken all over the country.
We've almost completed the inner loop.
We've already seen plans for an outer loop.
And though there's none under construction, we now have freeway presentations and freeway proposals being looked at for other arteries of this community.
And I think that runs counter to the master plan.
But yet, everything continues in spite of that.
It also seems to run counter to the master plan that
growth is to be managed, but at the same time, clean industries are courted without real regard for the consequences of their relocation in the Austin area.
Is that a significant problem?
Yes, and it's significant from two points.
One is that the city planning department is not involved in planning for the economic growth of this community.
That's not a role that they've had.

the Chamber of Commerce, through its economic development activities, has been the recruiter, will remain the recruiter, and goes out and gets these people, then the issue before the planning department has characteristically been, is this appropriate land use, and can we serve it with utilities?
If the answer is yes, they go there.
So, it's reactive.
It's reactive planning, and that's what's unfortunate about Austin.
We find ourselves looking down the road in a master plan, but because, as I view it, it's vague, we are constantly reacting to what industry wants to go where.
We don't have a land use map of saying, no, you can only go here.
Changes have occurred in the master plan, in the maps, and in zoning to accommodate those industries.
As a result of their relocation.
As a result of their proposal to come to the city, having been recruited by the Chamber of Commerce.
How about the role of heavy industry as part of the economic base there?
They have not come to Austin because the Chamber of Commerce has determined, and they will tell you, we're members of the Chamber.
To the extent that Austin is Austin and we want to keep it that way, the Chamber of Commerce has taken the role that they should bring new jobs for the expanding population.
They don't want heavy industry, and the city doesn't want heavy industry.
So as a result, heavy industry doesn't come here because they won't recruit them.
They do feel their responsibility is to Central Texas more than it is to the city of Austin because the Travis County people do not believe in growth control.
And we are seeing plants built north of the city outside the city limits in Round Rock and in areas north of there because this is a regional question and not

In that regard, in planning, there has not been an agreement at the Capital Area Planning Council who may have a responsibility to look at the regional aspects of growth and the regional aspects of development.
There has not been, to my knowledge, any dialogue that would come up with an agreed-upon plan for the regional development of this area of the state.
As a result, everybody's out fighting each other.
With the...

With these incoming electronic industries, with the great number of governmental employees that are in the Austin area, I would imagine that the average income level is higher than it would be for most other Texas cities.
Is that the case?
And how does the income level of the residents relate to planning decisions?
Well, I'm not sure what you could say about the average income of Austin.
It's difficult to compare it with Houston.
It's higher than San Antonio.
Houston and Dallas I'm not sure of.
Other cities of half a million, Fort Worth or so, I'm not sure of that either.
The relative wealth of the community is important in Austin because that determines where federal funds are to be spent.
And that is very closely watched.
But as far as the average income of Austin being higher than
than other comparable cities.
I don't think that's the case, but I don't know.
University professors aren't paid all that much.
There's a lot of them.
State employees, I don't know, the top salary may be $40,000 a year.
That's not significant.
But having so many people that...
There aren't many in that level, though.
There aren't very many in the $40,000 level, but I don't know.
It's not like being in Dallas and having insurance and banking executives making hundreds of thousands of dollars.
Have there been problems in the past as far as federal grants programs and minority groups and getting their acceptance of these programs in their areas?
There's been problems with one, but beyond that there's been a general problem, and it relates to income.
The city does not have a, is not considered a distressed city.
It doesn't fall into a Laredo category or a San Antonio category.
There is not a tremendously widespread incidence of poverty.
There are a lot of poor people, but there are a lot of people who are not poor.

And so Austin's problem has been one that many of the federal programs designed to help those who need help, and we have a significant number, are not eligible for Austin to apply for because we do not have sufficient
poverty, we do not have sufficient decay to meet the criteria.
Austin has forever fought that.
To say that we have 25,000 people who are poor, and just because we don't have 56,000, which was 30% of the population or so, we shouldn't be singled out and not allowed to get those benefits.
And we've fought forever to do that.
Austin has had a great history of participation in federal programs.

The only one that I'm aware of that was defeated by the reluctance or opposition of minority groups has been the overall economic development plan, which involved EDA funds that would have allowed planning and public works funds.
The suspicion was that this was a program to build downtown at the expense of the poor.
The poor would be used as an excuse to gain eligibility.
But once that eligibility was granted,
It was a mistrust that the council would actually use the funds for their benefit.
We'll never know if that was valid because as a result of their opposition, the council voted not to pursue the matter.
And so after about a year, the minority groups indicated that they felt they were being used and didn't want to be done that way unless there was some guarantees they could control the program.
The council said that they didn't feel that was an appropriate role.
And so they decided not to submit the application.
And as a result, the groups that were intended to be benefited suffered.
I believe so.
I know that at least $200,000 in federal planning assistance for economic development did not come to this city, of which advance approval had already been granted.
And that occurred when?
January 1978.
Is there anything else that you think is significant as regards Austin and planning and elements in its history that have affected planning here?
I think there are issues right now before the city that the citizens and the commissions refuse to acknowledge or fail to understand.

The community in its master plan has determined that it should be a compact city to avoid the problems of sprawl and to encourage and protect its inner city neighborhoods and the residential quality of the city.
That means you've got to have higher densities in a compact city, and you've got to accommodate growth corridors, and you've got to take care of mass transit.
It's the only way to avoid sprawl.
But while they say that, on one hand, they have repeatedly voted to prohibit increased densities in the inner city and to attempt to limit heights and densities of developments.
And the two are violently and totally opposite.
It sounds like irreconcilable differences in a divorce contest.
Very similar.
And unfortunately, what has occurred from that is while those loggerheads have existed, the community wants integrity.

compact growth they want managed growth but they don't want any higher densities as a result of that major new developments are occurring four five six miles from the city center in the southwestern part of the city a very sensitive area a giant mall three malls announced within a mile of each other huge office centers being proposed high density apartments being built the same in the northwest community and i believe that as uh
As should be learned, if one were to look at Houston with a high density core and then other nodes of high densities, Austin is heading right down the same line and has yet to recognize that.
As far as problems between planning for Travis County and planning for Austin City, are there significant, you mentioned earlier,
that Travis County is more growth-oriented.
They're not concerned particularly with growth management.
They want more population.
Has that come into conflict with the goals of Austin City on occasion?
Yes, it has.
The county has not established a formal planning department program.
They've had people who've carried out that responsibility from time to time.
But the county has been in conflict with the city on occasion
primarily in regards to its transportation programs.
Where the new highways are going, should freeways be built, and where are those freeways?
The county has supported those while the city has expressed reservations and concern.
Those have been resolved sometimes in split votes and other activities at the Austin Transportation Study Level, which is the Metropolitan Planning Organization for Transportation.
City planning doesn't play a direct role in that either.
That has been a transportation role directed by the Transportation Department of the city, and there have been many, many conflicts.
Have there been occasions for joint Austin City and Travis County Planning Commission meetings to decide this type of area-wide problem?
There's no planning commission in Travis County.
Oh, I'm sorry, there's no commission.
No, the only thing they have is the Travis County Commissioner's Court.
There has never been, to my knowledge, any joint meeting with the planning commission.
There has been only on occasion informal meetings between the county commissioners and the city council.
So needs and goals don't exist in the county.
Don't exist.
And that often comes in direct conflict with what Austin City has envisioned and planned for.
Yeah, let me give you a very concrete example.
During the Jeff Friedman Council there was a long discussion about Mopac Boulevard from its northern
well from its point of town lake south through the Martin Creek area, a very environmentally sensitive area.

The city's position was that the thing should be built with limited access and no frontage roads so that it did not encourage growth along the corridor and would therefore be just a transportation link and absolutely nothing else like a parkway through a park.
It was outside the city limits so the city could not exercise any kind of direct controls.
The county, however, agreed with the construction of the highway as it would normally be, frontage roads, bridges, and all that.
Since the county was purchasing the right-of-way, they were the ones who were the deciding issue.
As a result, the highway is now built, will almost be open in the next few months or so.
We'll have frontage roads, exit ramps, all of the things that will lead to a further densification of the area.
And that was a direct conflict.

beyond the city of Austin's control because it was outside the city limits and totally under the discretion of the county, who had other constituents, had industries, had other activities that said, we need that highway.
And it was done that way.
The same thing's occurring in far west Travis County as future planning is taking place for new loop freeways.
The city of Austin has not supported those, has not even voted on them.
Yet the planning continues in spite of the master plan that says do not grow into the western part of the county.
Well, thank you very much for your time, and I appreciate your opinions on this.
Good.
The information you've given us.
You're welcome.
